description:
'''Brian Michael Firkus''' (born August 23, 1989), better known by the stage name '''Trixie Mattel''', is an American [[drag queen]], television personality, singer-songwriter, DJ, and entrepreneur originally from [[Marinette County, Wisconsin]]{{efn|name="hometown"|Mattel has variously cited origins in different Marinette County municipalities, including [[Wausaukee, Wisconsin|Wausaukee]],<ref>{{Cite web |last=Maas |first=Tyler |date=January 28, 2022 |title=Trixie Mattel's "This Town" video captures the sweetness and darkness of rural Wisconsin |url=https://milwaukeerecord.com/music/trixie-mattels-this-town-video-captures-the-sweetness-and-darkness-of-rural-wisconsin/ |access-date=February 8, 2022 |website=Milwaukee Record |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Crivitz, Wisconsin|Crivitz]],<ref name="undercover2019">{{cite AV media |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=g25sf_GmKaU |title=Trixie Mattel Replies to Fans on the Internet |date=May 8, 2019 |publisher=[[GQ]]|type=video |time=4:07 |via=YouTube}}
</ref> and [[Silver Cliff, Wisconsin|Silver Cliff]].<ref name="factcheck2024">{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?si=RO8lJYplNv2Jdbwy&v=VWVOP1c2Bn8&feature=youtu.be |title=Who is Trixie Mattel? Trixie Fact Checks Her Wikipedia Page |date=December 9, 2024 |last=Mattel |first=Trixie |type=video |time=2:28 |via=YouTube}}
</ref> }}. She{{Efn|Mattel uses ''[[she/her]]'' pronouns while in drag, and ''[[he/him]]'' pronouns otherwise.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Cardenas |first=Cat |date=July 8, 2022 |title='By the Rules of Nature, I Shouldn't Be Here': The Unlikely Rise of Trixie Mattel |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/trixie-mattel-blonde-pink-albums-motel-interview-1369575/ |access-date=February 4, 2024 |magazine=Rolling Stone |language=en-US}}</ref>}} is known for her exaggerated, [[1960s in fashion|1960s-influenced]] style, distinctive eye makeup, and musical repertoire that blends comedy with acoustic pop and folk-country music, with skills in guitar and the [[autoharp]]. In 2015, she competed in the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)|seventh season]] of the [[Drag (clothing)|drag]] reality television competition series ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'' and returned to win the [[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars (season 3)|third season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars]]''. Mattel has also made guest appearances in various iterations of the [[Drag Race (franchise)|''Drag Race'' franchise]], additionally appearing as a judge on the spinoff series ''[[Queen of the Universe (TV series)|Queen of the Universe]]'' (2021–2023).

Mattel formed the popular [[comedy duo]] known as [[Trixie and Katya|Trixie and Katya]] alongside fellow drag queen and frequent collaborator [[Katya Zamolodchikova]]. Together, they starred in the [[World of Wonder (company)|World of Wonder]] web series ''[[UNHhhh]]'' (2016–2023) and its [[Viceland]] spin-off ''[[The Trixie & Katya Show]]'' (2017–2018). The pair also host the [[Netflix]] review web series ''[[I Like to Watch]]'' (2019–present) and the podcast ''[[The Bald and the Beautiful]]'' (2020–present).

Mattel's music style began as primarily [[Folk music|folk]] and [[Country music|country]], with her first and second studio albums, ''[[Two Birds (album)|Two Birds]]'' (2017) and ''[[One Stone]]'' (2018), both charting on the [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] Folk Albums chart at No. 16. She went on to star in the documentary film ''[[Trixie Mattel: Moving Parts]]'' (2019). Her third studio album, ''[[Barbara (Trixie Mattel album)|Barbara]]'' (2020), featured an "[[Folktronica|electro-folk]]" sound, while her fourth studio album, ''[[The Blonde & Pink Albums]]'' (2022), was a [[double album]] featuring a "[[power pop]]" sound.  Her musical comedy special, ''Trixie Mattel: One Night Only'' (2020), was nominated for a [[Critics' Choice Television Award]]. She also produced and starred in the renovation docuseries ''[[Trixie Motel]]'' (2022–2024), which chronicled the opening of her own [[Palm Springs]] resort of the same name.

Co-published with Zamolodchikova, Mattel's first book, ''[[Trixie and Katya's Guide to Modern Womanhood]]'' (2020), became a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' bestseller]]. She appeared on ''[[New York Magazine]]''<nowiki/>'s list of "The Most Powerful Drag Queens in America", ranking fourth. She also operates a YouTube channel focused on beauty, featuring frequent collaborations with fellow drag queens and various celebrities such as [[Iggy Azalea]], [[Nicole Byer]], [[Brittany Broski]], [[Rebecca Black]] and [[Margaret Cho]]. Mattel's business ventures include being the founder, sole owner and CEO of Trixie Cosmetics, a cosmetics brand launched in 2019. Her persona is inspired by her love of [[Barbie]] dolls; she owns a large collection of Barbies that she has shared in videos on her YouTube channel.
